segments.text: That first fall?
I don't think any of our family came down here to visit.
Both his family and my family had been here various times.
When I came to visit the campus in the years, in the previous years, my mother had brought, had come down here with me.
In fact, I stayed at the MSC with my mother for one of the dances that I came down.
I did come down for one of the, at least one of the dances, maybe two.
and his parents came down at least one time and for a football game and for final review, we all came down and saw the final review.
Then when did y'all go, did y'all go home for Thanksgiving?
Yes, we did.
The game, and if I remember correctly that, because I know that we came back shortly and lived here, but I believe we won the game
No, the thing was we lost the game, but we played well and we got the Monday off.
I think that was it.
We lost, but we played well and we got the Monday off.
Then you went home for Christmas.
Yes.
And then came back, studied for finals.
That's right, we did.
It was the whole year was different than it is now.
Was there a kind of a support mechanism, system?
Was there anybody?
Where did you turn if you wanted to learn more about this course or to prepare for it?
Who did you go to for advice?
Actually, I think basically I relied on my husband because he had been here for four years before that.
He had been active not only in the Corps.
He'd spent four years in the Corps even though he didn't have a contract.
The vet students couldn't have a contract because they went to school in the summer.
And he was one of the ones that entered vet school after two years of pre-vet.
Not all of them were able to do that.
But he had also been active on campus and served on the MSC Council.
and as a class officer.
And so whenever I needed advice, I pretty much just turned to him.
And so you said that nine hours you did well in two and not as well in the other.
What about the second semester?
The second semester, because I'd done well in history, I went and got special permission to take an upper division history class.
the second American history class and an upper division world history class, early class.
I think it ended at 500, Greek or Roman here, and a math class.
And so I still took nine hours.
I had decided to get a job and I found a job

When I realized how little I was making, because I had worked the year before when I was a senior in high school, I eventually gave up my job because it just didn't seem like it was worth the money that I was bringing.
I think I was earning 60 cents an hour or something like that, but I had decided that
that that's really what I wanted.
And by that time, I knew that we were leaving as soon as he graduated in August.
Okay.
You remained in Hensel the whole year.
Yes.
Did you ever witness any student pranks, Good Bull, any of the?
You know, I probably didn't see anything like that.

My experiences dealing with the students, Hensel didn't have that, I mean we didn't have that, but my experiences dealing with student events really when I decided to run for freshman class early in the semester, I guess in September,
Yes, September.
Yeah, describe that.
Okay.
Well, since my husband had been an officer and I thought, well, A&M's opening up and having females, they might as well have a female run for office.
And I had been active in high school and done things, and so I decided to run for social secretary.
I figured that that would be something that a female might be
capable of doing and I filed the papers and nobody ever said anything and my husband said, I know what you do, how you run for office and we'll take care of this.
And generally what he, the first time we were going to go and we were going to, I was going to talk to some of the freshmen so he went to the dorm
And he told the, I guess, the duty officer of the day that he had someone to speak to the freshmen for a freshman class office.
And this is, I assume, the way it was done.
And then the duty officer would get all the freshmen in the dorm together and, of course, he didn't tell them that it was a female that was going to speak to them.
And we went to several different dorms and I had a,
not a prepared speech, but I introduced myself, told them where I was from, what I'd done, and I was rather dressed up.
I remember I had on heels that night.
We did this several times, and we had a discussion about whether he was going to tell them that it was a female or whether he wasn't going to tell them it was a female.
In one particular dorm,
He, of course, he had said, I think it's better, we'll get a better turnout, although they're going to make the freshmen come anyway.
But one of the times, sometimes it was very crowded and I couldn't see very many of the students other than the ones that were just in the front.
In one particular dorm, it was the area was larger.
And I was standing there and I'm beginning to see the freshmen file in.

and then it was getting crowded and but I could still see what was happening and all of a sudden I noticed that there were two young men who had towels on and I assumed that was all that they had on and when they realized that there was a female standing in front then they kind of were
inching over so that they were behind other people in the dorm.
And after that happened, I said, you tell them that this is going to be a female because, you know, this is embarrassing for them and for me.
But nobody ever said anything to me.
Nobody said, you shouldn't be doing this.
We had our election and I was not elected.
ended up coming in towards the end.
I don't even remember.
I'd have to read the articles again.
The paper called me a Maggie.
They didn't call me an Aggie because they hadn't decided whether we could be Aggies or not.
The one thing I do remember is that one of the other officers that was elected that
during that election was Henry Cisneros because he was in that class.
I don't believe I ever met him, but he was.
That class had a number of very bright Hispanics because A&M had gone out to recruit, not with a shotgun but with a rifle, that one, that one, that one, and that one.
And then as seniors
they almost took over the campus.
Hector Gutierrez was the first corps commander, Henry I think was band commander or something like that, over and over and over.
Did you put out any signs, campaign posters?
I don't remember that we did that.
If we did it, it was low key, it was not
We might have put things on some of the bulletin boards, but we didn't put things on the ground or in stakes or anything like that.
Did you have a campaign slogan?
No, I didn't.

I just said that I pretty much told everybody that since I was, that I thought that a woman could handle the office of social secretary for the class, and I just explained some of the experience that I had earlier.
Did anybody ever ask you a ridiculous question or an insulting question from an audience?
No, I think most of the audience were so stunned when they saw me and I would say, I'd ask at the end of my presentation if anybody had any questions.
I remember being asked just one or two times different things, you know, if I'd forgotten to where are you from or, you know, things like that.
But I think these freshmen were just so stunned that they were coming down to listen to a female, not in a bad sense, but just it was a surprise.
Now, were the comparatively small number of co-eds in your classes and so forth, did you feel lonely, lonesome?
I think that I was brought up in a way that it prevented me from having
that feeling.
I could be friends with the guys and I know there were times when we would go have coffee together, some of the ones that were in my classes.
We'd go have coffee at the MSC occasionally and talk.
And I think that the way I was raised contributed to that.
My mother had a

a BBA degree from the University of Texas so she was probably one of very few women in her program and because she was in business and I had been raised to speak to adults and I never had any problem and I always I mean I was equal to them so I never had any problem and I have friends I'd always had
male friends even.
I mean in high school I had male friends.
Right now I'm going to ask you a dumb, stupid, naive question.
Was your Jewish background in fact a strength to you for this?
That might have been true.
I'm saying about being an individual, being self-reliant.
Right.
And I will make a comment.
My husband had said one time that being an Aggie was kind of like being Jewish because you, at that time, we were, you know, the Aggies were minorities.
They were, when you got together, people were always kind of, oh, an Aggie.
I mean, not that they would do that as a Jew, but you just felt different if you were an Aggie.
And so that's possibly the way it was.

The other thing was that I think that because my mother had a college education, which might have been because she was Jewish, although there were plenty of Jewish women who didn't, but a lot of them did, it made it easy for me to be in an academic setting and that I always felt equal to any situation.
You're here only a year at that point.
I'm looking for questions.
You mentioned Henry Cisneros.
Were there any other celebrities, people who became so, that you remember?
I don't remember anybody else.
Did you meet Henry that year?
It's possible that I did.
I don't remember.
I think I might have because we had some meetings of the ones that were going to run for office.
So I believe that we did meet each other.
I was looking at your questions and I don't know whether you want me to go ahead.
Yeah, please do.
You asked about the campus hospital and that year, this goes back to whether they expect women or not.
That year there was an outbreak and I want to say maybe hepatitis at San Houston State or over in Huntsville, I believe.
But wherever it was and whatever the disease, they had asked all of the students to get vaccinated.
Or actually, it might have been a gamma-globin shot.
and so they asked us to go to the hospital and I remember the old hospital I think I'm remembering right it had an open double doors and there was kind of a foyer in the front and we were
out the door, down the block, there was a long line of us.
And there, I don't, I didn't remember seeing any other females in that line.
But I had gotten in the line, I think my mom called and said, you go get it.
So I got in line with all the other guys and the nurses were inside and they had not expected a female.
And what they were doing was they were having the guys come through the door
dropped their pants and they were giving them a shot right there.
They weren't taking them to an examining room.
And all of a sudden they realized that there's a female right there standing there.

So they had to quickly, you know, stop what they were doing, escort me to a different room, and then I went out a back door so that I didn't disrupt this continual setup that they had arranged so that it was
It was less time consuming.
They could just, once they got them in the doors, they could give real shots and all.
But that's another incident where they had not, things were still not in place for females or there were no contingencies for females.
It was like the bathroom situation and where.
Oh, yeah, where were there restroom facilities for women in the classroom buildings then?

The things that I remember having to do was to go find the office, wherever the office was in that building, and specifically I remember Nagel Hall, and having to then go to the secretaries, and generally the female, the restrooms were locked, they weren't marked, and you had to have a key.
And so the secretary would then walk you down the hall, unlock the door, and show you where
where the bathrooms were.
I do remember that specifically in Nagel.
I don't remember, I know that I was in, I had a class in the academic building and in animal industries.
I don't remember looking in those other two buildings, but generally that was what you had to do.
Now, in most of your classes, both semesters, how many women were there in the class?
When I took the upper level history class, there were
a few other women in that class.

I'm assuming that most of the women who came here that year had been going to Sam or someplace like that and when A&M opened up they didn't have to travel anymore and that these were a little bit older than I am and because I was so young, I was only 18, there were very few married
18-year-olds and so I didn't have any in my classes except that.
And the only bad situation I had, had to do with that kind of situation.
And do you have any guess as to what percentage of the undergraduate women were married and were single?
Since I didn't meet very many of them, it's only a guess, but I would think that the majority of these were not the daughters of the faculty member.
They were student wives.
Student wives, yes.
that were living in Hensel.
And I met some wives who were seniors at Sam and didn't want to transfer and were still commuting.
So there were more married students, but they still continued to go to St. Houston.
I see you got some other notes there.
Well, I told you about going to the hospital.
We also, I burned my hand and I ended up having to go over there.
that was a different situation.
They took care of me and it was early in the morning.
I remember Guyon Hall and we attended plays there that the university put on.
They would have calls for people who were interested and I was enthralled by the building.
I thought it was a gorgeous building and it had
they were kind of faded but it was red plush seats and actually my husband's graduation took place in Guyon Hall, the vet school's graduation took place in Guyon Hall.
So I was, I had fond memories of Guyon Hall and when they announced that they were tearing it down I was saddened.
One of the other things that we participated in was when, was as a student when you bought this packet of all the things that you were entitled to you got the
I think it was called Town Hall Series, and we would see the presentations that they brought and put on in the basketball arena in G. Raleigh White.
And I can't remember what his, he's the New Orleans trumpeter.
Pete Fountain?
No, it's the other, shoot, it's not Fountain, it's the big one.
But he came and I remember, of course, it wasn't air conditioned and we were sitting way up at the top and the windows were open.
But you could hear him way up there.
But we did, I think that the students that wanted to had, did take advantage of those kind of things and traveling.
Did you all go to any movies?
If so, where?
I do remember going to,
Not to the theater, I mean not inside theaters here.
We went to the drive-in a couple of times.
Oh.
We went to, and I also, and I also went to.
The Grove?
Yeah, I've been to the Grove.
We would go to the Grove and take your mosquito repellent.
But occasionally we went to the Grove for things in the spring or something.
Did you go to the drive-in here at north side of the campus?
I think it was off of Texas Avenue, but I'm not sure where it was.

And one of the other things that we did was, that was kind of a splurge, was going, and we went one night when it was just freezing cold and had problems seeing the movie, you know, because of the, but we would put our nickels in a jar and when we'd have enough nickels, we would go around the corner from Hansel

And I don't remember whether it was a kettle, but there was a little restaurant, and we would have pie and coffee at, say, 10 or 10.30 at night, just at the end of the day, when we have enough extra nickels.
Where did you do your grocery shopping?
Piggly Wiggly, generally just across the street, which was over there, right close to Hensel.
I would occasionally go into Bryan, and I can't remember what grocery store, but I watched the specials, and we could get five cans of tuna fish for a dollar, or three cans for a dollar.
But a lot of times I just went over to Piggly Wiggly, which I believe was just right across Texas Avenue.
Well, I think we've covered a lot of the things.

I did say that I told you about the football games and one of the things, we went home to Shreveport probably once during the fall semester and then Thanksgiving and then a couple of times in the spring semester.
And I know that I was scared silly when my husband decided to pick up a hitchhiker, but he was in his Aggie uniform, so he did, you know, we did.
and that was all right.
I was, when you talked about notable personalities on campus, I do remember Pinky Downs, but I also remember Ranger, and...
Describe each of those.
Well, Pinky Downs seemed to be everywhere.
Whenever you went to an event, he was there, and the official greeter, I think, is what his title was, and whatever it was, if it was a dance or any kind of event on campus,
He seemed to be there all the time.
And it was strange to me, I was going, who is this guy, you know?
I mean, I'd seen him before when I had been here, but the other notable person that we all knew, Ranger.
And... Make believe I didn't know who Ranger was.
Ranger was President Rutter's dog, and he was the ugliest bulldog you ever, I think he was a bulldog, but he was the ugliest dog you ever saw, and he had the run of the campus.
I mean, Reveille was always,

kept on a leash, but Ranger just roamed around and attended classes with students regularly, especially since all the classrooms were opened, or many of them were opened because the campus wasn't air-conditioned.
And I know that when I had class in the Animal Industries building, he would

I'm not sure exactly how he got in because there were steps to get into that building and into that room but he joined us in that building and I remember more than one time that he was in the classroom and everybody would pat him and I don't remember feeding him or anything but he certainly didn't look like he needed to be fed but he was a gentle member of the
student body I guess you'd say, or an honored member.
Did you go to Silver Taps?
Yes, I attended Silver Taps.
I cannot remember whether there was one specifically for anybody that we knew, but I did attend Silver Taps.
I've recently attended another Silver Taps.
I don't remember it being quite as long, the ceremony being quite as long.
I don't remember.
You mean then?
It's longer now?
I think it's longer now.
But I could be, it could have been that my legs were tired this last time.
And we attended Muster, and I'd already attended Muster before, but an entry for it.
We attended Muster, it was held that year on the front lawn of the administration building and the student body sat out on the lawn there.
And it was held, I believe it was still light, so I believe it was earlier perhaps than it is now.
I think that's true.
But we did have it right there, so it's not the, and it was,
It was just as important as it is now.
I think that it was a simpler service than it is now.
And it's a very profound service.
What about Bonfire?
Did you go to Bonfire?
I had attended at least one other Bonfire.
I was, yes, we, I'm trying to remember the game.
This was the year after Kennedy died, so the year before was when the bonfire didn't burn.
And this year we did have bonfire, yes, and I was there.
Because we didn't go home until later, and so I did attend.
Keep going.
Well, I think that we got to,
I'm trying to see what else I can, after I've told you about Ranger and I'm glad that Ranger has a distinct spot on the campus because I thought he was, and the muster.
That was, I've attended a lot of musters and that's one that stands out in my memory.
I've attended a muster in London.
But that one does stand out in, let's see.
This question, describe the student body in general.
As far as you at that point, Aggies came from where?
Were they rural or urban?
I think it was in flux actually.
I believe that a lot of the, although
most of the Jewish students were urban, of course, and there were no farm boys.
The population in general was still beginning, was just beginning to start coming from the bigger cities.
I, and the problem with this is that, with my answer to that question is that my mom was a Texan and I,
I also had heard stories about what she said during the Depression about who attended A&M.
But I primarily believe that a lot of them, they were beginning to leave, they would not be the farm boys, but there were still a lot of small town rural people and not the overwhelming majority of
urban people, the students that there are now, which I know is true.
You saw a Hispanic?
Yes.
As a matter of fact, my husband's best friend in that school was a Hispanic.

they got to be friends because my husband's name was Goldman and his name was Garcia so they sat next to each other and in fact I had stayed at their house he was married and he was an older student who had been an undergraduate here earlier and had gone back to vet school as a little bit older student and so he and his wife taught school here and so yes I did see Hispanics on the campus
And coming from the south, that was not unusual for me, although I didn't come from Texas.
We had Hispanics in the school system, even though it was a segregated school system.
Were there any blacks at A&M that fall?
I don't believe so.
I don't remember seeing any there.
Were you aware of any Asian, either Asian American or Asian nationals?
It seems to me that there might have been some Asian graduate students here already by then, and that we saw a few Asians here.
And whether or not they were Asian Americans or whether they were non-natives, I don't really know, but I do remember seeing
some, you know, around the campus in the library and things.
And I'm assuming very few international students.
Yeah, yeah.
So that's why I wouldn't, I would guess that these were Asian Americans, but I don't know for sure.
It could have been a few from.
Let's see.
Now, College View, those were the old World War II barrack-like.
Right.
And do you have any idea how extensive, how big, how many people were in College View, you reckon?

I don't know because College View, since that was the, those were the ones that, that I said I wouldn't live in because they had fires in those since I was, Hensel was made out of cinder blocks and I figured it wasn't going to burn, so.
Oh, I see.
Hensel was over on?
Hensel was north of the school and,
East of the, of college.
East of college, yeah.
And College View was also, there were those, they were wooden barracks like.
Now there were some other wooden housing for married graduate students that were over where the police station used to be and on the south side of the campus.
But the vet students weren't considered graduate students.
And we didn't qualify for that housing.
And I don't know whether those were bigger or not.
But I have an idea they might have been two bedrooms.
But actually, the College View, the wooden barracks, I
